            number: 1,
            title: "State the Decision Explicitly",
            description: "Write the decision down in a single sentence: 'I am deciding whether to [specific action].' Vague decision framing — 'I am thinking about maybe changing directions on X' — makes reversibility assessment impossible. The decision must be explicit before it can be classified. This step alone reduces misclassification significantly by forcing clarity about what is actually being decided."
          },
          {
            number: 2,
            title: "Assess the Four Reversal Dimensions",
            description: "For each of the four dimensions — financial cost, time cost, relationship/reputational cost, and opportunity cost — score the cost of reversing this decision on a simple three-point scale: Low (reversal costs less than 10% of original commitment), Medium (reversal costs 10-50% of original commitment), or High (reversal costs more than 50% of original commitment or is structurally impossible). Score each dimension independently before looking at the overall pattern."
          },
          {
            number: 3,
            title: "Apply the Classification Rule",
            description: "If all four dimensions score Low: this is a high-reversibility decision. Set a time limit of thirty minutes maximum for deliberation, make the decision, and build a review point (one week or one month, depending on the decision's natural feedback cycle) to assess and adjust. If any dimension scores High: this is at minimum a medium-reversibility decision. Deliberate proportionally to the severity of the High dimension. If multiple dimensions score High: treat as genuinely irreversible and apply full structured analysis."
          },
          {
            number: 4,
            title: "Match Process to Classification",
            description: "High-reversibility decisions: decide within your time limit, implement, set a review point. Do not seek additional opinions or gather more data after the time limit expires — the review point is your feedback mechanism. Medium-reversibility decisions: apply a structured framework (options expansion, values clarification, outside view) but impose a decision deadline of one to two weeks. Do not allow the deliberation to extend indefinitely. Genuinely irreversible decisions: run the full process — pre-mortem, second-order thinking, outside view, decision journal entry — before committing. No artificial time constraint."
          },
          {
            number: 5,
            title: "Document the Classification and Review It",
            description: "Record your reversibility classification and the reasoning behind it in a decision journal. When the decision's outcome becomes clear — at your review point for reversible decisions, or over time for irreversible ones — revisit the classification. Were you right about the reversal costs? If you consistently misclassify decisions in one direction (typically treating reversible choices as irreversible), that pattern is diagnostic of loss aversion or status quo bias and warrants deliberate correction."
          }
        ]} />
      </section>

      <section id="misconceptions">
        <h2>Common Misconceptions About Decision Reversibility</h2>

        <h3>Misconception 1: "Most Important Decisions Are Irreversible"</h3>
        <p>
          This is almost always false — and it is one of the most damaging beliefs in decision-making. The vast majority of decisions that feel important and high-stakes are actually highly reversible. Career experiments, relationship boundaries, productivity systems, investment allocation within liquid assets, creative directions, communication approaches — these feel important because they connect to things that matter, but they are not irreversible. Confusing importance with irreversibility is a primary driver of paralysis and under-action. A decision matters to you; that does not mean it cannot be corrected if it goes wrong.
        </p>

        <h3>Misconception 2: "If You Can Imagine a Way Back, the Decision Is Reversible"</h3>
        <p>
          Reversibility is not about theoretical possibility — it is about practical cost. There is almost always some theoretical path back from any decision. You can theoretically sell a house, leave a marriage, change a career, or abandon a business. The question is what that reversal actually costs in the four dimensions described above. Many decisions that are technically reversible are functionally irreversible because the reversal cost is so high that it would rarely be exercised. Treating technically-reversible-but-practically-irreversible decisions as two-way doors produces the same under-deliberation errors as treating genuinely irreversible decisions casually.
        </p>

        <h3>Misconception 3: "Reversible Decisions Don't Need a Framework"</h3>
        <p>
          The framework for reversible decisions is different from the framework for irreversible ones, but it is still a framework. For reversible decisions, the framework is: decide quickly, implement fully, set a review point, and update based on actual feedback. The error is not applying no framework to reversible decisions — the error is applying the wrong framework, specifically the heavy deliberation process appropriate for irreversible decisions. Reversible decisions deserve a fast, committed trial followed by genuine assessment, not endless deliberation followed by a half-hearted implementation that produces misleading feedback. For more on building a complete decision system, see our guide to <a href="/blog/mental-models">mental models for better decision making</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>Misconception 4: "Reversibility Means You Don't Have to Think About Failure"</h3>
        <p>
          Reversibility reduces the stakes of being wrong, but it does not eliminate the value of thinking about failure modes before acting. Even for highly reversible decisions, a brief pre-mortem — imagining the decision produced a poor outcome and identifying the most likely cause — often reveals simple modifications that would significantly improve the probability of success. The difference is the time investment: for a reversible decision, five minutes of pre-mortem thinking is appropriate; for an irreversible one, a structured thirty-minute exercise is warranted. The concept is the same; the depth is calibrated to stakes. For a complete treatment of the pre-mortem technique, see our dedicated analysis of <a href="/blog/how-billionaires-decide">how elite decision-makers stress-test choices before committing</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

